<div class="library-tome-centered">
<div>Every creator needs a foundation, a framework, or a theme that ties their work together. For me, that framework is mythology. It‚Äôs the landscape I‚Äôve chosen to work on, the battlefield I‚Äôve set for myself, and the wrapper that holds my creations together. Even as my focus shifts toward philosophy, this mythological theme remains at the heart of my identity as a storyteller.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>---</div><div><br></div><div>1. Why Mythology?</div><div><br></div><div>Mythology is timeless. It‚Äôs not just stories of gods, heroes, and ancient worlds‚Äîit‚Äôs a lens through which we explore universal truths, human nature, and the mysteries of existence. By grounding my creative world in mythology, I‚Äôm tapping into something that resonates deeply with people across cultures and eras.</div><div><br></div><div>But it‚Äôs more than that. Mythology is how I see myself. I imagine myself as a character within a mythological world, wielding the lyre as an ancient bard might, creating stories and philosophies to share with others. It‚Äôs not just a theme‚Äîit‚Äôs a part of who I am and how I present myself to the world.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>---</div><div><br></div><div>2. The Landscape I Created</div><div><br></div><div>When I began creating, I focused heavily on mythology. I made videos about myths, explored ancient stories, and built a foundation steeped in this timeless theme. Over time, my focus shifted toward philosophy, personal reflections, and exploring the human condition.</div><div><br></div><div>Even though I don‚Äôt always focus on mythology now, the landscape I created still shapes everything I do. It‚Äôs the wrapper around my work‚Äîthe cohesive theme that ties it all together. Whether I‚Äôm discussing the Philosophy of Emergence, writing love letters, or sharing personal insights, it all exists within the mythological world I built.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>---</div><div><br></div><div>3. Working Within This Framework</div><div><br></div><div>Choosing a mythological theme gives my work continuity and identity, but it also comes with challenges. It limits what I can do, in a way, because I have to ensure everything fits within the theme. However, these limitations are also what make it exciting‚Äîthey force me to be creative, to find ways to connect any topic to the mythological world I‚Äôve created.</div><div><br></div><div>For example:</div><div><br></div><div>Philosophy Through Mythology: I explore modern ideas like the Philosophy of Emergence through the lens of ancient myths, showing how timeless truths still apply today.</div><div><br></div><div>Personal Stories as Myths: I frame my own journey as a kind of myth, casting myself as a character navigating a larger story.</div><div><br></div><div>The Lyre as a Symbol: Playing the lyre connects me to the ancient bardic tradition, blending music and storytelling in a way that feels authentic to my theme.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>This framework isn‚Äôt a restriction‚Äîit‚Äôs a creative landscape that inspires me to think differently and create in ways that feel cohesive and meaningful.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>---</div><div><br></div><div>4. Being a Storyteller in a Mythological World</div><div><br></div><div>At the heart of it all, I see myself as a storyteller. My stories might not always be about gods or heroes, but they‚Äôre about life, meaning, and the struggles we all face. By framing my work within a mythological world, I‚Äôm inviting others into a shared story‚Äîone that‚Äôs timeless yet deeply personal.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>---</div><div><br></div><div>5. The Mythology Evolves</div><div><br></div><div>Mythology itself evolves, and so does the mythological world I‚Äôve created. It‚Äôs no longer just about ancient stories‚Äîit‚Äôs about philosophy, creativity, and exploring what it means to live a meaningful life. The landscape I created is adaptable, allowing me to grow and change while still maintaining a sense of identity and continuity.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>---</div><div><br></div><div>6. Why This Matters</div><div><br></div><div>This mythological wrapper isn‚Äôt just for me‚Äîit‚Äôs for my audience, too. It creates a sense of intrigue and cohesion, inviting people into a world that‚Äôs rich with meaning and possibility. Whether they‚Äôre exploring my playlists, reading my blog, or watching my videos, they‚Äôre stepping into a story that‚Äôs bigger than any one piece of content.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>---</div><div><br></div><div>Closing Thoughts</div><div><br></div><div>The mythological landscape I‚Äôve created is my creative battlefield, my lens for viewing the world, and my way of sharing stories that matter. It‚Äôs not just a theme‚Äîit‚Äôs a foundation, a wrapper, and a journey.</div><div><br></div><div>Even as my work evolves, this landscape remains the constant thread that ties it all together. It‚Äôs the world I chose to create, and it‚Äôs the world where I‚Äôll continue to create for as long as I can.</div>
